  pages={1-7},
  abstract={The recent scaling of Internet of Things (IoT) in smart cities generates massive volumes of real-time data. This creates significant challenges to existing task offloading strategies regarding latency, scalability, and resource efficiency. While cloud offers high scalability, its dependence on distant infrastructure often results in long delays. On the other hand, edge computing enhances responsiveness; however, it struggles under heavy workloads. Additionally, smart cities generate different types of data with differing priorities, an aspect that current offloading strategies fail to address. To address these challenges, this paper proposes a dynamic task offloading framework based on Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO), having a hierarchical architecture of computing resources (Edge, Regional, and Cloud). The proposed agent dynamically allocates tasks according to system feedback, including delay, service cost, service utilization, and the priority of data. Simulation results show that our model effectively reduces delay, optimizes resource utilization, and facilitates priority-aware task offloading across heterogeneous tiers.},
