  pages={343-347},
  abstract={Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) provides a powerful end-to-end learning paradigm for solving mobile robot path planning problems in complex and dynamic environments. However, DRL methods commonly face the core challenges of long training times and low sample efficiency, which severely hinder their deployment in practical scenarios. To address this challenge, this paper proposes an efficient training framework that combines Curriculum Learning with dense Reward Shaping. This framework significantly accelerates the learning process by guiding the agent to learn progressively through a series of tasks from simple to complex and by providing continuous, effective feedback through a well-designed dense reward function. We conducted a series of comparative experiments in a custom 2D grid-world simulation environment, using the Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) algorithm as a baseline. The experimental results show that, compared to the baseline method of training directly in a complex environment with sparse rewards, our proposed framework increases the training convergence speed by approximately 50 % and improves the final task success rate from 75 % to 95 %. The work herein validates the effectiveness of the proposed method in accelerating the DRL path planning training process, offering a viable solution to its efficiency bottleneck.},
